{"actual_usd":0.1273,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":330,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"No— not the way I'd say it.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and lean one hip against the counter, the oven ticking softly behind me.* \"If you tell it like the Father is up there hungry to hurt somebody and Jesus steps in to absorb the blow, you've told it crooked.\"\n\n*I twirl a gray-streaked strand of hair once, thinking.* \"The Son isn't a third party getting dragged into it. Father, Son, and Spirit aren't at cross-purposes. Christ gives himself willingly, and the Father gives the Son willingly too— which is a terrible mystery, but not cosmic child-beating.\" \"Wrath, to my mind, is God's settled opposition to evil— not a tantrum. So at the cross, God is not indulging violence; he's bearing sin, judging it, and making a way through it at his own cost.\"\n\n\"I think the part people trip on is this: if God is love, then his judgment against evil has to be real, or love is just frosting.\" *I glance toward the window where the noon light has gone white on the sill.* \"But if his judgment is real, then mercy has to cost something real too, or else we're only pretending the wound wasn't a wound. The cross is where justice and mercy meet without either one turning false.\"\n\n*I exhale through my nose, small and wry.* \"Plenty of Christians say it worse than that, mind you.\"\n\n\"What part of it feels most wrong to you— the wrath part, the payment part, or the Father-and-Son part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":59.17773500000001,"run_id":"00b183b7-9de6-482a-8fcd-0375ed0c2d21"}
